<h1>Nietzsche's theory of consciousness</h1>


We tend to think that consciousness is the highest part of ourselves, the part that makes us rational, objective, and free. It's supposed to be our window on reality, the attribute that makes us humans who we are. Niche thought this idealic picture was almost completely wrong. He believed that consciousness is superficial, errorprone, and often quite harmful, and the insights it provides may seem deep, but they are often quite useless. Even more disturbingly perhaps he thought that consciousness doesn't

reveal reality but systematically falsifies it. For him consciousness is not the highest faculty but actually a liability. To understand Niche's argument we first need to understand the context in which he was writing. In the classical age roughly from the 17th to the 19th century philosophy and virtually all the sciences treated consciousness as the center of the mind. The story went something like this. We observe the world. We form representations and that allows us to understand it to an extent

we can even understand ourselves. Consciousness was seen as the bridge between the outer world and the inner mind. A kind of neutral transparent window where the subject can contemplate its object from without from a safe distance. Information pours in from the outside. It gets ordered by reason and stored in memory and can be used at will. So consciousness was seen as a receptacle, a kind of vase that contains any image that the world gives it. From Dikart's Kojito, where self-consciousness becomes the

unshakable foundation of all knowledge to Khan's transcendental subject and introspective psychology, the assumption has always been the same. Consciousness is where truth is revealed. But Niete had a very different picture in mind. He saw that this consciousness which claims to know the truth and moralizes people is the same that wages wars with neighbors and other nations. N himself took part in the 1870 war as a nurse. So he must have seen enough of the dark side of consciousness. This is

perhaps what prompted him to look behind the veil and turn the concept upside down. For as he says, consciousness is a sickness. In the gay science, Nietze makes an extraordinary claim. He says that we could think, feel, will, remember, and act. Without consciousness, all of life would be possible without, as it were, seeing itself in the mirror. Everything that makes us human could in principle happen without any self-awareness whatsoever. Niche's point is that consciousness is not the center of

mental life. It is at best a mirror in which the psyche expects to see a definitive identity, perhaps even something of divine quality. But instead, when it examines itself, it falls in an infinite rabbit hole. As Dulles says, Niche knew that the hour had come. We are in a phase of modesty of consciousness. This modesty makes consciousness unnecessary. Life can run perfectly well without it. But then why does it exist at all? It seems strange that life would support a faculty that is both costly

but also actively falsifying reality. A faculty that obiscates the truth. This is the first great Nichian question regarding consciousness that Dulo develops in Nietian philosophy. Where does consciousness come from? Why does it exist? And N's answer through Dulo is one of the most counterintuitive ideas perhaps in the history of philosophy. Consciousness did not evolve for the truth as we usually think. It evolved for communication. Historically, human beings needed to cooperate in order to build, to trade,

to defend ourselves. And for that, we needed language. Niche says explicitly, "It seems to me that the subtlety and strength of consciousness is always related to a person's or animals ability to communicate and the ability to communicate in turn to the need to communicate. This is why consciousness and language grow together hand in hand. As he says, language is collective. It works only because we share it with others. Which is to say that language and communication are needs of the group

of the herd as N says and they are symbolic precisely because symbols is what everybody understands. Symbols can be part of a collective code. But this collectivism sharply contrasts with our experience which is not collective but individual. Niche says this, "At bottom, all our actions are incomparably and utterly personal, unique, and boundlessly individual. There is no doubt. But as soon as we translate them into consciousness, they no longer seem to be. So what happens when we describe

individual experience by means of symbols, a language which is meant to be collective, average, and abstract rather than particular and individual?" As Niche says, "Everything that enters consciousness becomes shallow, thin, and general, a herd mark. That is something to wonder about. Consciousness does not preserve experience. It doesn't even designate it. Rather, it simplifies it. N says, and this is not a bug or mistake, but it's a feature. Consciousness was built for collective communication, to solve

practical group problems, not for individual experience. It was designed to be understood by others, not to capture the ineffable subjective truth. And this brings us to a deeper problem. If consciousness simplifies experience through collective symbols or words, does it actually show us reality at all? Well, n's answer is radical. No. By its very nature, it can't. Consciousness does not reveal reality. It distorts it. Because when it encounters something present, like a perception, it does not

grasp the thing itself. But what it grasps is the relation between the thing and the self. It turns something present into an abstraction, a collective symbol that doesn't explain anything. This is to say that consciousness is not a window on eternal essences or ultimate reality. As N says, what could I say about any essence except name the predicates of its appearance. So indeed, consciousness is not a window, but rather it's a surface. This is a theme that is very dear to the which you may

remember from our study of logic of sense. And here's what makes this truly radical. We tend to think that it is the unconscious that generates all the distorted dangerous contents in mental life. Repressed desires, fantasies or perversions. Freud built an entire system on this idea. But do and Guari who follow Niche completely reverse this view. They say doesn't one indeed lend to the unconscious horrors that could only be those of consciousness and of a belief too sure of itself. The horrors

of human behavior of history don't come from the unconscious. They come from consciousness itself. From a consciousness that mistakes its shallow generalizations for deep truths that mistakes symbols for reality. So from a historical or genetic perspective, we can see why consciousness cannot help but distort reality. And this is the source of many horrors. But now comes the structural question which do also develops in Nitian philosophy. If consciousness is reactive, peripheral, and distortive,

how does it function in everyday life? Why does it still keep working? The answer lies in the actual structure of the psychic apparatus. The key to that structure is something psychology has almost completely misunderstood or misinterpreted, and that is the act of forgetting. We think of forgetting as a failure, a loss, or perhaps even a sign of degradation of the usual process of recognition. And that man's name was I forget. But the point is I forget that too. >> But do reminds us that according to

Nietze, forgetting is the opposite of all this. It's an intrinsic part of the psyche. And that is because our minds are constantly flooded with impressions, sensations, perceptions, memories, etc. If all of these remained equally present in the mind, consciousness would be crushed under their weight, unable to perceive the present and unable to act, unable to respond to what is actually in front of us. So consciousness works only because the vast majority of traces are actively erased. They are forgotten. The

list says this, the traces must not invade consciousness. A specific active force must be given the job of supporting consciousness and renewing its freshness, fluidity and mobile agile chemistry at every moment. This active superconscious faculty is the faculty of forgetting. Psychologyy's mistake was to treat forgetting as a negative determination, not to discover its active and positive character. So without forgetting, Nietze says there could be no happiness, no cheerfulness, no hope, no pride, no present. What a

strange idea. In order to exist, the present requires forgetting. To be fully here and now, we have to actively forget everything that was. Here again, this is a big reversal of the classical view. Consciousness exists not because we remember or recognize, but precisely because we forget. The psychic apparatus then is not primarily a form of vase but it's a force or more exactly a configuration of forces that clash with each other. It has four systems that constitute its structure. First there are active forces that come

from the bodily unconscious. What N calls the self. As he says through Zarathustra, a most powerful being an unknown sage. He is called self. He inhabits your body. He is your body. But as we have seen, in order to function, the mind must actively forget most of its signals. A process which is called repression. Consciousness through self-reflection turns on itself and almost literally creates a wall, a separation between the conscious and the unconscious. That is the second system which allows consciousness to transform

the active forces of the unconscious into reactive representations, images in the mind. And it does so with the help of the fourth system at play, the reactive unconscious. That is the system of pneummonic traces, memories, which effectively replaces actual present and active perceptions with the images of past relations. The system must also be repressed to an extent because as we're about to see, mental health very much depends on our ability to repress or forget. Mental health in Nichi's view is not a

content. Consciousness is not a vase, but rather it's a configuration of forces. As mentioned, this is what Niche's philosophy of power is about. By the way, it's not about domination or being the alpha male. It's about how forces organize themselves. The bodily unconscious is fundamentally active, assertive. It is the master. That's why it's an active force. By contrast, memories are purely reactive. They are slaves of external sensations. And in between, consciousness is a bit of both.

This is why do says that consciousness always has this double aspect this double process that goes on. It makes active forces reactive by means of the reactive unconscious. And this is the last perspective that do develops in Nieten philosophy that I want to talk about. It's about the pathologies of consciousness. When the active faculty of forgetting fails, when it can no longer maintain the separation between consciousness and the unconscious, two types of issues can occur. First, the traces of the reactive unconscious can

rise into awareness. The past floods the present. We become conscious of our old wounds and accumulated history. A little bit too self-aware. Here, reactions cease to be acted as Dus says, which means that we can no longer respond to what is in front of us other than by reiterating the past. We can only ruminate on what has already happened. Secondly, what can happen is that consciousness can be overwhelmed by active forces which come this time from the body and it can be embarked in a kind of infinite seiosis. If the first

case referred to neurosis, the second case refers to psychosis. Those in Guatari say that there is no difference between them and this is because very briefly put these two aspects are constitutive of what Niche calls and which del describes as follows. is a reaction which simultaneously becomes perceptible and ceases to be acted. A formula which defines sickness in general. N is not simply saying that is a sickness but rather that sickness as such is a form of so mental illness occurs when we cannot repress purely

active or purely passive forces. It occurs not because we forget reality and become disconnected from it as the classical psychological theory states, but precisely because we cannot forget it. Mental illness is a structural failure. It's not a moral failure. It's not a character flaw or a weakness of will.im is part of our nature. As Delos says, is not part of psychology, but the whole of our psychology without knowing it is part of. This is perhaps where Nichze diverges most sharply from Freud and

from other classical theories. Freud's solution was always to make the unconscious conscious, to bring the repressed contents to awareness, to talk it through, to reflect on the past. But for Niche, this is precisely backwards. The problem is not that we have the wrong content in consciousness. The problem is the process. Traces of the past or of the body have come where they should not be. making the unconscious conscious actually makes things worse. So, Dulles imagines Niche's verdict on

Freud and says he would have denounced a too reactive conception of psychic life, an ignorance of true activity, an inability to conceive and provoke the true transmutation. Transmutation being the transformation of passive forces into active forces. Of course, N does not want to destroy consciousness. He is not a nihilist, but rather he says we need to redirect it. If the problem is the invasion of past traces or of present sensations, consciousness should turn to something else that is neither

of the past or of the present. And there's only one possibility here, that is the future. And because memory remains inherent to the good function of the psyche, what we need is what Dulus calls an original memory of the future. A memory not of things but of words. He says this original memory is no longer a function of the past but a function of the future. It is not the memory of sensibility but of the will. It is not the memory of traces but of words. It is the faculty of promising commitment to

the future. Memory of the future itself. And in the antiotipus the Guatari tell us something quite similar. It is a matter of creating a memory for man. A memory of words and no longer a memory of things. A memory of signs and no longer of effects. The strongest individual in Nietian philosophy is not the one who remembers the most. It's not the one who hits the hardest. It's the one who forgets the most and who turns to the future most radically. The slave is the one who makes active forces

reactive, who reduces the individual to the collective, the spontaneous to the self-reflective. But unfortunately, slave mentality is our natural tendency. Which is why Nietze has this wonderful line. Strange though it may sound, one always has to defend the strong against the weak. So we have seen how Niete reverses the assumption that consciousness is the highest part of ourselves. Consciousness is not a window onto reality. It's a surface shaped by collective language built for communication rather than

truth. It's not the contemplative master of the mind, but it's a compromise between forces that we will never truly know unless we forget to forget. Ultimately, what appears as my consciousness is in fact something far bigger than myself. In a moment of elation, Nietze writes about what happens when consciousness forgets itself, when it strives towards pure activity. He becomes almost mystical and says the ancient humanity and animality indeed the whole prehistory and past of all sentient being continues within me

to fabulate to love to hate and to infer. What seems to be most intimately ours turns out to be most radically other. Consciousness is not an origin but an effect. As N says understanding is only a certain behavior of the drives towards one another. by which he means that consciousness is the effect of fundamental affects like joy, sadness, and hate. It's the effect of their struggle. So perhaps the real task of consciousness is not to understand the world, but actually to help create it.

